# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tacacs-plus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] Authentication is concerned with proving identity, authorization with granting permissions, accounting with maintaining a continuous and robust audit trail via logging.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] Common network protocols providing this functionality include TACACS+, RADIUS, and Diameter.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] In some related but distinct contexts, the term AAA has been used to refer to protocol-specific information.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] For example, Diameter uses the URI scheme AAA, which also stands for "Authentication, Authorization and Accounting", as well as the Diameter-based Protocol AAAS, which stands for "Authentication, Authorization and Accounting with Secure Transport".
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] These protocols were defined by the Internet Engineering Task Force in RFC 6733 and are intended to provide an AAA framework for applications, such as network access or IP mobility in both local and roaming situations.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] However, the AAA paradigm is used more widely in the computer security industry.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] AAA servers in CDMA data networks are entities that provide Internet Protocol (IP) functionality to support the functions of authentication, authorization and accounting.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] The AAA server in the CDMA wireless data network architecture is similar to the HLR in the CDMA wireless voice network architecture.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] Current AAA servers communicate using the RADIUS protocol.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] As such, TIA specifications refer to AAA servers as RADIUS servers.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] While at one point it was expected that Diameter was to replace RADIUS, that has not happened.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] Diameter is largely used only in the mobile (3G/4G/5G) space, and RADIUS is used everywhere else.
[src:tacacs-plus/aaa-computer-security] The behavior of AAA servers (radius servers) in the CDMA2000 wireless IP network is specified in TIA-835.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The name is a play on words, derived from the RADIUS protocol, which is the predecessor (a diameter is twice the radius).
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Diameter is not directly backward compatible but provides an upgrade path for RADIUS.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Also: Like RADIUS, it is intended to work in both local and roaming AAA situations.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] It uses TCP or SCTP, unlike RADIUS which uses UDP.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Unlike RADIUS it includes no encryption but can be protected by transport-level security (IPSEC or TLS).
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The base size of the AV identifier is 32 bit unlike RADIUS which uses 8 bit as the base AV identifier size.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Like RADIUS, it supports stateless as well as stateful modes.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Like RADIUS, it supports application-layer acknowledgment and defines failover.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Diameter is used for many different interfaces defined by the 3GPP standards, with each interface typically defining new commands and attributes.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] A *Diameter Application* is not a software application but is a protocol based on the Diameter base protocol defined in RFC 6733 (obsoletes RFC 3588) and RFC 7075.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Each application is defined by an application identifier and can add new command codes and/or new mandatory AVPs (Attribute-Value Pair).
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Adding a new optional AVP does not require a new application.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] communicate using the Diameter protocol.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol was initially developed by Pat R.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Calhoun, Glen Zorn, and Ping Pan in 1998 to provide a framework for authentication, authorization, and accounting (AAA) that could overcome the limitations of RADIUS.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] At the time Diameter was designed, RADIUS was believed to have issues with reliability, scalability, security, and flexibility.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] RADIUS also did not support large policies which were needed for telephony applications.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol defines a policy protocol used by clients to perform Policy, AAA, and resource control.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] This allows a single server to handle policies for many services.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Like RADIUS, Diameter provides AAA functionality, but uses TCP and SCTP instead of UDP, therefore delegating detection and handling of communication problems to those protocols.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol is enhanced further by the development of the 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS).
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The S6a, S6b, Gx, Gy, Sy, Rx, Cx, Dh, Dx, Rf, Ro, Sh and Zh interfaces are supported by Diameter applications.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Through the use of extensions, the protocol was designed to be extensible to support proxies, brokers, strong security, mobile IP, network-access servers (NASREQ), accounting and resource management.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The Diameter base protocol is defined by RFC 6733 (Obsoletes: RFC 3588 and RFC 5719) and defines the minimum requirements for an AAA protocol.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] *Diameter Applications* can extend the base protocol by adding new commands, attributes, or both.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Diameter security is provided by IPsec or TLS.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The IANA has assigned TCP and SCTP port number 3868 to Diameter, as stated in section 11.4 of RFC 6733.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The packet consists of a Diameter header and a variable number of Attribute–Value Pairs, or AVPs, for encapsulating information relevant to the Diameter message.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] This field indicates the version of the Diameter Base Protocol.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] As of 2014, the only value supported is 1.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The Message Length field indicates the length of the Diameter message in bytes, including the header fields and the padded AVPs.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The "**R**" (Request) bit – If set, the message is a request.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The "**P**" (Proxiable) bit – If set, the message MAY be proxied, relayed or redirected.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] If cleared, the message MUST be locally processed.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The "**E**" (Error) bit – If set, the message contains a protocol error, and the message will not conform to the CCF described for this command.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Messages with the "E" bit set are commonly referred to as error messages.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] This bit MUST NOT be set in request messages.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The "**T**" (Potentially re-transmitted message) bit – This flag is set after a link failover procedure, to aid the removal of duplicate requests.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] It is set when resending requests not yet acknowledged as an indication of a possible duplicate due to a link failure.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Each command Request/Answer pair is assigned a command code.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Whether it is the request or answer is identified via the 'R' bit in the Command Flags field of the header.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The values 0-255 are reserved for RADIUS backward compatibility.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The values 256-16777213 are for permanent, standard commands allocated by IANA.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The values 16777214 and 16777215 (hex 0xFFFFFE and 0xFFFFFF) are reserved for experimental and testing purposes.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] A Command Code is used to determine the action that is to be taken for a particular message.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Application-ID is used to identify for which Diameter application the message is applicable.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The application can be an authentication application, an accounting application, or a vendor-specific application.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Diameter agents conforming to a certain Diameter extension publicize its support by including a specific value of in the Auth-Application-ID Attribute of the Capabilities-Exchange-Request (CER) and Capabilities-Exchange-Answer (CEA) command.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The value of the Application-ID field in the header is the same as any relevant Application-ID AVPs contained in the message.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] For instance, the value of the Application-ID and of the Auth-Application-ID Attribute in the Credit-Control-Request (CCR) and Credit-Control-Answer (CCA) Command for the Diameter Credit-Control Application is 4.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The Hop-by-Hop Identifier is an unsigned 32-bit integer field (in network byte order) that is used to match the requests with their answers as the same value in the request is used in the response.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol requires that relaying and proxying agents maintain transaction state, which is used for failover purposes.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Transaction state implies that upon forwarding a request, its Hop-by-Hop Identifier is saved; the field is replaced with a locally unique identifier, which is restored to its original value when the corresponding answer is received.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The request's state is released upon receipt of the answer.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Received answers that do not match a known Hop-by-Hop Identifier are ignored by the Diameter agent.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] In case of redirecting agents, the Hop-by-Hop Identifier is maintained in the header as the Diameter agent responds with an answer message.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The End-to-End Identifier is an unsigned 32-bit integer field (in network byte order) that is used to detect duplicate messages along with the combination of the Origin-Host AVP.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] When creating a request, the End-to-End Identifier is set to a locally unique value.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The End-to-End Identifier is not modified by Diameter agents of any kind, and the same value in the corresponding request is used in the answer.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] For simplicity, AVP Flag "**V**" bit Means **Vendor Specific**; "**M**" bit means **Mandatory**; "**P**" bit means **Protected**.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The "**V**" bit, known as the Vendor-Specific bit, indicates whether the optional **Vendor-ID** field is present in the AVP header.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] When set the AVP Code belongs to the specific vendor code address space.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The "**M**" bit, known as the Mandatory bit, indicates whether support of the AVP is required.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] If an AVP with the "**M**" bit set is received by a Diameter client, server, proxy, or translation agent and either the AVP or its value is unrecognized, the message *must* be rejected.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Diameter Relay and redirect agents *must not* reject messages with unrecognized AVPs.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The "**P**" bit indicates the need for encryption for end-to-end security.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The RFC 3588 defines a core state machine for maintaining connections between peers and processing messages.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] This is part of the basic protocol functionality and all stacks should support it and as such abstract from the connectivity related operations.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Additionally, application specific state machines can be introduced either later or at a higher abstraction layer.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The RFC 3588 defines an authorization and an accounting state machine.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The communication between two diameter peers starts with the establishment of a transport connection (TCP or SCTP).
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The initiator then sends a Capabilities-Exchange-Request (CER) to the other peer, which responds with a Capabilities-Exchange-Answer (CEA).
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] For RFC3588 compliant peers TLS (Transport Layer Security) may optionally be negotiated.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] For RFC6733 compliant peers TLS negotiation may optionally happen before the CER/CEA.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The connection is then ready for exchanging application messages.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] If no messages have been exchanged for some time either side may send a Device-Watchdog-Request (DWR) and the other peer must respond with Device-Watchdog-Answer.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] Either side may terminate the communication by sending a Disconnect-Peer-Request (DPR) which the other peer must respond to with Disconnect-Peer-Answer.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] After that the transport connection can be disconnected.
[src:tacacs-plus/diameter-protocol] The Diameter protocol is currently defined in the following IETF RFCs: Obsolete RFCs are indicated with strikethrough text.
[src:tacacs-plus/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:tacacs-plus/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:tacacs-plus/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:tacacs-plus/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:tacacs-plus/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:tacacs-plus/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:tacacs-plus/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:tacacs-plus/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:tacacs-plus/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS is a client/server protocol that runs in the application layer, and can use either TCP or UDP.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Network access servers, which control access to a network, usually contain a RADIUS client component that communicates with the RADIUS server.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS is often the back-end of choice for 802.1X authentication.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] A RADIUS server is usually a background process running on UNIX or Microsoft Windows.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The Blast-RADIUS attack breaks RADIUS when it is run on an unencrypted transport protocol like UDP.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS is an AAA (authentication, authorization, and accounting) protocol that manages network access.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS uses two types of packets to manage the full AAA process: Access-Request, which manages authentication and authorization; and Accounting-Request, which manages accounting.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Authentication and authorization are defined in RFC 2865 while accounting is described by RFC 2866.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The user or machine sends a request to a Network Access Server (NAS) to gain access to a particular network resource using access credentials.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The credentials are passed to the NAS device via the link-layer protocol—for example, Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) in the case of many dialup or DSL providers or posted in an HTTPS secure web form.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] In turn, the NAS sends a RADIUS *Access Request* message to the RADIUS server, requesting authorization to grant access via the RADIUS protocol.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] This request includes access credentials, typically in the form of username and password or security certificate provided by the user.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Additionally, the request may contain other information which the NAS knows about the user, such as its network address or phone number, and information regarding the user's physical point of attachment to the NAS.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The RADIUS server checks that the information is correct using authentication schemes such as PAP, CHAP or EAP.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The user's proof of identification is verified, along with, optionally, other information related to the request, such as the user's network address or phone number, account status, and specific network service access privileges.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Historically, RADIUS servers checked the user's information against a locally stored flat file database.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Modern RADIUS servers can do this, or can refer to external sources—commonly SQL, Kerberos, LDAP, or Active Directory servers—to verify the user's credentials.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The RADIUS server then returns one of three responses to the NAS: 1) Access Reject, 2) Access Challenge, or 3) Access Accept.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The user is unconditionally denied access to all requested network resources.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Reasons may include failure to provide proof of identification or an unknown or inactive user account.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Requests additional information from the user such as a secondary password, PIN, token, or card.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Access Challenge is also used in more complex authentication dialogs where a secure tunnel is established between the user machine and the Radius Server in a way that the access credentials are hidden from the NAS.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Once the user is authenticated, the RADIUS server will often check that the user is authorized to use the network service requested.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] A given user may be allowed to use a company's wireless network, but not its VPN service, for example.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Again, this information may be stored locally on the RADIUS server, or may be looked up in an external source such as LDAP or Active Directory.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Each of these three RADIUS responses may include a Reply-Message attribute which may give a reason for the rejection, the prompt for the challenge, or a welcome message for the accept.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The text in the attribute can be passed on to the user in a return web page.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Authorization attributes are conveyed to the NAS stipulating terms of access to be granted.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] When a client is configured to use RADIUS, any user of the client presents authentication information to the client.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] This might be with a customizable login prompt, where the user is expected to enter their username and password.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Alternatively, the user might use a link framing protocol such as the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP), which has authentication packets which carry this information.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Once the client has obtained such information, it may choose to authenticate using RADIUS.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] To do so, the client creates an "Access- Request" containing such Attributes as the user's name, the user's password, the ID of the client and the port ID which the user is accessing.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] When a password is present, it is hidden using a method based on the RSA Message Digest Algorithm MD5.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] When network access is granted to the user by the NAS, an *Accounting Start* (a RADIUS Accounting Request packet containing an Acct-Status-Type attribute with the value "start") is sent by the NAS to the RADIUS server to signal the start of the user's network access.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] "Start" records typically contain the user's identification, network address, point of attachment and a unique session identifier.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Periodically, *Interim Update* records (a RADIUS Accounting Request packet containing an Acct-Status-Type attribute with the value "interim-update") may be sent by the NAS to the RADIUS server, to update it on the status of an active session.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] "Interim" records typically convey the current session duration and information on current data usage.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Typically, the client sends Accounting-Request packets until it receives an Accounting-Response acknowledgement, using some retry interval.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The primary purpose of this data is that the user can be billed accordingly; the data is also commonly used for statistical purposes and for general network monitoring.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS facilitates this by the use of *realms*, which identify where the RADIUS server should forward the AAA requests for processing.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] A realm is commonly appended to a user's user name and delimited with an '@' sign, resembling an email address domain name.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] This is known as *postfix* notation for the realm.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Another common usage is *prefix* notation, which involves prepending the realm to the username and using '\' as a delimiter.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Modern RADIUS servers allow any character to be used as a realm delimiter, although in practice '@' and '\' are usually used.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Realms can also be compounded using both prefix and postfix notation, to allow for complicated roaming scenarios; for example, somedomain.com\username@anotherdomain.com could be a valid username with two realms.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Although realms often resemble domains, realms are arbitrary text and need not contain real domain names.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Realm formats are standardized in RFC 4282, which defines a Network Access Identifier (NAI) in the form of 'user@realm'.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] In that specification, the 'realm' portion is required to be a domain name.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] However, this practice is not always followed.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] When a RADIUS server receives an AAA request for a user name containing a realm, the server will reference a table of configured realms.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] If the realm is known, the server will then *proxy* the request to the configured home server for that domain.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The behavior of the proxying server regarding the removal of the realm from the request ("stripping") is configuration-dependent on most servers.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] In addition, the proxying server can be configured to add, remove or rewrite AAA requests when they are proxied over time again.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Proxy Chaining is possible in RADIUS and authentication/authorization and accounting packets are usually routed between a NAS Device and a Home server through a series of proxies.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Some of advantages of using proxy chains include scalability improvements, policy implementations and capability adjustments.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] But in roaming scenarios, the NAS, Proxies and Home Server could be typically managed by different administrative entities.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Hence, the trust factor among the proxies gains more significance under such Inter-domain applications.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Further, the absence of end to end security in RADIUS adds to the criticality of trust among the Proxies involved.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Roaming with RADIUS exposes the users to various security and privacy concerns.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] More generally, some roaming partners establish a secure tunnel between the RADIUS servers to ensure that users' credentials cannot be intercepted while being proxied across the internet.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] This is a concern as the MD5 hash built into RADIUS is considered insecure.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS is transported over UDP on ports 1812 and 1813..
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RadSec (RADIUS over TLS) uses TCP port 2083 by default.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The RADIUS packet data format is shown to the right.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The fields are transmitted from left to right, starting with the code, the identifier, the length, the authenticator and the attributes.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The Identifier field aids in matching requests and replies.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The Length field indicates the length of the entire RADIUS packet including the Code, Identifier, Length, Authenticator and optional Attribute fields.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The Authenticator is used to authenticate the reply from the RADIUS server, and is used in encrypting passwords; its length is 16 bytes.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The RADIUS Attribute Value Pairs (AVP) carry data in both the request and the response for the authentication, authorization, and accounting transactions.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The length of the radius packet is used to determine the end of the AVPs.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS is extensible; many vendors of RADIUS hardware and software implement their own variants using Vendor-Specific Attributes (VSAs).
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Microsoft has published some of their VSAs.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] VSA definitions from many other companies remain proprietary and/or ad hoc, nonetheless many VSA dictionaries can be found by downloading the source code of open source RADIUS implementations, for example FreeRADIUS.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] For example, some vendors drop the "Vendor Length" field, or they use 2 octets for the "Vendor Type" and/or the "Vendor Length" fields.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RFC 8044 Section 3.14 defines the "vsa" data type which mandates the RFC 2865 Section 5.26 format.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The RADIUS protocol transmits obfuscated passwords using a shared secret and the MD5 hashing algorithm.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] As this particular implementation provides only weak protection of the user's credentials, additional protection, such as IPsec tunnels or physically secured data-center networks, should be used to further protect the RADIUS traffic between the NAS device and the RADIUS server.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The RadSec protocol addresses the issue with legacy RADIUS/UDP security by "wrapping" the RADIUS protocol in TLS.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] However, the packets inside of the TLS transport still use MD5 for packet integrity checks and for obfuscating the contents of certain attributes.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The Blast-RADIUS attack breaks RADIUS when it is transported by plain UDP by attacking MD5 within RADIUS.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Another recommended mitigation is to require Message-Authenticator attributes for all requests and responses.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] CVE-2024-3596 has been assigned for the Blast-RADIUS attack.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] As more dial-up customers used the NSFNET a request for proposal was sent out by Merit Network in 1991 to consolidate their various proprietary authentication, authorization and accounting systems.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Among the early respondents was Livingston Enterprises and an early version of the RADIUS was written after a meeting.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The early RADIUS server was installed on a UNIX operating system.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Livingston Enterprises was acquired by Lucent Technologies and together with Merit steps were taken to gain industry acceptance for RADIUS as a protocol.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Both companies offered a RADIUS server at no charge.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] In 1997 RADIUS was published as RFC 2058 and RFC 2059, current versions are RFC 2865 and RFC 2866.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The original RADIUS standard specified that RADIUS is stateless and should run over the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] For authentication, it was envisaged that RADIUS should support the Password Authentication Protocol (PAP) and the Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol (CHAP) over the Point-to-Point Protocol.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Passwords are hidden by taking the MD5 hash of the packet and a shared secret, and then XORing that hash with the password.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The original RADIUS also provided more than 50 attribute-value pairs, with the possibility for vendors to configure their own pairs.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The choice of the hop-by-hop security model, rather than end-to-end encryption, meant that if several proxy RADIUS servers are in use, every server must examine, perform logic on and pass on all data in a request.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] This exposes data such as passwords and certificates at every hop.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS servers also did not have the ability to stop access to resources once an authorisation had been issued.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Subsequent standards such as RFC 3576 and its successor RFC 5176 allowed for RADIUS servers to dynamically change a users authorization, or to disconnect a user entirely.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Now, several commercial and open-source RADIUS servers exist.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Features can vary, but most can look up the users in text files, LDAP servers, various databases, etc.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Accounting records can be written to text files, various databases, forwarded to external servers, etc.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] SNMP is often used for remote monitoring and keep-alive checking of a RADIUS server.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] RADIUS proxy servers are used for centralized administration and can rewrite RADIUS packets on the fly for security reasons, or to convert between vendor dialects.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The Diameter protocol was intended as the replacement for RADIUS.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] While both are Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting (AAA) protocols, the use cases for the two protocols have since diverged.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Diameter is largely used in the 3G space.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] One of the largest barriers to having Diameter replace RADIUS is that switches and access points typically implement RADIUS, but not Diameter.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] Diameter uses SCTP or TCP while RADIUS typically uses UDP as the transport layer.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] As of 2012, RADIUS can also use TCP as the transport layer with TLS for security.
[src:tacacs-plus/radius] The RADIUS protocol is currently defined in the following IETF RFC documents.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS was originally developed in 1984 by BBN, later known as BBN Technologies, for administration of ARPANET and MILNET, which ran unclassified network traffic for DARPA at the time and would later evolve into the U.S.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] Cisco Systems began supporting TACACS in its networking products in the late 1980s, eventually adding several extensions to the protocol.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] In 1990, Cisco's extensions on top of TACACS became a proprietary protocol called Extended TACACS (XTACACS).
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] Although TACACS and XTACACS are not open standards, Craig Finseth of the University of Minnesota, with Cisco's assistance, published a description of the protocols in 1993 as IETF RFC 1492 for informational purposes.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS is defined in RFC 1492, and uses (either TCP or UDP) port 49 by default.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS allows a client to accept a username and password and send a query to a TACACS authentication server, sometimes called a TACACS daemon.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] It determines whether to accept or deny the authentication request and sends a response back.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] The TIP (routing node accepting dial-up line connections, which the user would normally want to log in into) would then allow access or not, based upon the response.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] In this way, the process of making the decision is "opened up" and the algorithms and data used to make the decision are under the complete control of whoever is running the TACACS daemon.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] Extended TACACS (XTACACS) extends the TACACS protocol with additional functionality.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] It also separates the authentication, authorization, and accounting (AAA) functions out into separate processes, allowing them to be handled by separate servers and technologies.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS+ is a Cisco-designed extension to TACACS that is described in RFC 8907.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS+ includes a mechanism that can be used to obfuscate the body of each packet, while leaving the header clear-text.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] Moreover, it provides granular control in the form of command-by-command authorization.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS+ has generally replaced TACACS and XTACACS in more recently built or updated networks.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS+ is an entirely new protocol which is not compatible with its predecessors, TACACS and XTACACS.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] There are a number of differences between the two protocols which make them substantially different in normal usage.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS+ can only use TCP, while RADIUS normally operates over UDP, but can also use TCP (RFC6613), and for additional security, TLS (RFC 6614) and DTLS (RFC7360).
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] One mode is where all traffic including passwords are sent in clear-text, and the only security is IP address filtering.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] The other mode is data obfuscation (RFC 8907 Section 4.5), where the packet header is clear-text, but the body including passwords is obfuscated with an MD5-based method.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] The MD5-based obfuscation method is similar to that used for the RADIUS User-Password attribute (RFC 2865 Section 5.2), and therefore has similar security properties.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] Another difference is that TACACS+ is used only for administrator access to networking equipment, while RADIUS is most often used for end-user authentication.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS+ supports "command authorization", where an administrator can log in to a piece of networking equipment, and attempt to issue commands.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] The equipment will use TACACS+ to send each command to a TACACS+ server, which can choose to authorize, or reject the command.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] Similar functionality exists in RADIUS in RFC 5607, but support for that standard appears to be poor or non-existent.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] TACACS+ offers robust functionality for administrator authentication and command authorization, but is essentially never used for authenticating end-user access to networks.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] In contrast, RADIUS offers minimal functionality for administrator authentication and command authorization, while offering strong support (and is widely used) for end-user authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:tacacs-plus/tacacs] As such, the two protocols have little overlap in functionality or in common usage.
